There are programming languages where something like pipe notation is all
but inevitable, being trivally programmer-definable.  What they have in
common is that a partially applied function is a function value, and the
pipe operator is semantically just another yawn ho-hum higher order
function with just another yawn ho-hum operator syntax.

R is not one of those languages, and indeed, with its approach to optional
and keyword arguments, it cannot be.    If I take for example lm(my.df),
that isn?t a function-expecting-formula-argument value, it?s an erroneous
function call.  This means that the pipe operator in R is *fundamentally*
different from similar operators in OCaml, F#, and Haskell.  To someone
used to those languages, this is confusing and annoying.

Pipe notation is in R, it?s staying in R, and it?s getting used in R.
But please, let?s not pretend that it?s not a xenotransplant that really
doesn?t fit R very well, any more than macros do.

