> You made me wonder if pipes add anything new to R. I happen to think they
> do and one argument to consider is that starting with the Magrittr pipe and
> on into the tidyverse, many people choose to use them quite a bit. Note
> that the ggplot2 graphics in various packages use something similar but
> different using a plus sign albeit a a pipe might have worked for that. I
> mean
>
> ggplot2(arg) + geom_xyz(args) + ...
>
> really means that you should create some complex data structure and ADD to
> is by having another function call implicitly take the data structure and
> make additions and changes to it and pass that along to the next and so on.
> The overloaded plus sign easily could have been avoided if all the
> functions (perhaps other than the first) had a first argument consisting of
> the structure being passed along.
>
> But you can make the argument you made in many parts of life. Is there
> much that cannot be done in earlier programming languages, albeit harder? I
> mean can you do much of what functions do without having functions? I
> recall doing some things in BASIC with GOSUB commands or other versions of
> GOTO, as well as in even more primitive ways in various assembly languages.
> Often if you need to do the same general things multiple times, you might
> cut and paste the same code repeatedly to where it is needed. Arguably, for
> MANY reasons, using functions has led to various forms of abstraction such
> as being able to pass a function as an argument to another so it can call
> an arbitrary thing at run time, or create factories that make functions of
> the fly or hand over a function to be called when an event happens, such as
> a mouse-over event, or even keep an array of functions to be called and
> later modify it on the fly.
>
> To me, yes, you could write most programs without pipelines. If you ever
> study some earlier pipeline methods in R, they took what you wrote and
> rewrote it without pipes. An example might be this:
>
> Results <- alpha(args) %>% beta(args) %>% gamma(args)
>
> This might be rewritten to something like:
> . <- alpha(args)
> . <- beta(., args)
> Results <- gamma(., args)
> # rm(.)
>
> Clearly, you could write your own code along those lines and perhaps
> instead use variable names like temp1 and temp2. But a well-designed
> implementation has the opportunity to speed things up and perhaps use less
> space overall as well.
>
> And, one beauty of a pipeline is the programmer and their though process.
> I have often taken an existing pipeline such as:
>
> Mydata %>%
>   Func1(...) %>%
>   Func2(...) %>%
>    Ggplot(....) +
>      Geom_line(...) +
>     ... +
>     Coord_flip(...)
>
> The meaning of it can be read fairly easily as you look down, especially
> if you indent things right. If having problems, you can often comment out a
> line and it usually continues to work well. You can often stick in a
> "print" between two lines and it will display a graph or something and pass
> the object along further in the pipeline, or remove it when not needed.
>
> This way of looking at things is often more natural to some of us. Base R
> has some fairly powerful tools that say let you select a subset of rows as
> as well as a subset of columns in notations like df[1:3, c(2,4,6,8)] and
> that is fine but another model uses more streamlined commands where each
> command does one or a few things that work together to get a result. One
> may select just rows and another may select just the columns, in a
> pipeline, or not in a pipeline. You can then insert an assortment of
> functions at the appropriate points that do things like mutate does or ask
> for grouping (or ungrouping) as well as functions that generate reports and
> so on. I can think both ways but mostly find the latter more appealing. Of
> course, if R had been written the latter ay, someone would likely have come
> up with a package to add the former way! LOL!
