We can define span(x) another way:
  span(x) = max {|a-b| | a \in x, b \in x}
This gives the same result as diff(range(x)) for logical x, integer x,
and double x, but it also works for complex x and in general for any
collection of elements of something that could be seen as a normed
vector spans.

This makes a good example of why it might be a bad idea to jump
prematurely to a definition in base R.

But there is another and more obviously statistical reason.  Consider
a time series.
diff(range(..)) makes sense on a (real, complex, multivariate) time
series, but the span of a time series
is more usually thought of as the span of *time* it is measured over.


